[src:monorepo-nx/build-automation] Build automation encompasses both sequencing build operations via non-interactive interface tools and running builds on a shared server.
[src:monorepo-nx/build-automation] Build automation tools allow sequencing the tasks of building software via a non-interactive interface.
[src:monorepo-nx/build-automation] A *build system* or *build automation tool* is a programming tool or set of tools that automate the compiling and linking of source code into an executable program or library.
[src:monorepo-nx/build-automation] They streamline the software development process by managing dependencies, resolving conflicts, and ensuring consistent builds across different environments.
[src:monorepo-nx/build-automation] When software projects grow complex, their build steps may involve multiple programming languages or compiling units, making manual build processes increasingly cumbersome.
[src:monorepo-nx/build-automation] Dependencies between code components necessitate careful ordering and potentially different tools for each piece.
[src:monorepo-nx/build-automation] Managing these dependencies manually can quickly lead to version conflicts, stale binaries, and difficulty tracking updates, making solutions such as shell scripts too difficult to maintain.
[src:monorepo-nx/build-automation] While individual developers might compile code directly, a robust build system is foundational to efficient software development in large organizations and teams, where automated builds become commonplace and most builds are triggered automatically rather than manually.
[src:monorepo-nx/build-automation] Given the essential role of build systems, it is said that they act as "repositories of essential build knowledge".
[src:monorepo-nx/build-automation] They effectively eliminate roadblocks and accelerate development velocity by enabling engineers to share resources and results.
[src:monorepo-nx/build-automation] An incremental build is a process within a build system where build tools use an incremental compiler to recompile only the parts of a software project that have changed since the last build, rather than rebuilding everything from scratch.
[src:monorepo-nx/build-automation] This optimization reduces build time by leveraging dependency tracking, caching, and selective compilation.
[src:monorepo-nx/build-automation] Incremental builds are especially valuable in large-scale software projects, where recompiling the entire codebase can be time-consuming and resource-intensive.
[src:monorepo-nx/build-automation] By identifying and compiling only the modified components—such as source files, libraries, or modules—the build system ensures faster iteration cycles, enabling developers to test and debug changes more efficiently.
[src:monorepo-nx/build-automation] The process relies on a dependency graph, which maps relationships between files, modules, or components in the project.
[src:monorepo-nx/build-automation] When a change is detected, the build system traverses this graph to determine which parts of the project are affected and need to be recompiled.
[src:monorepo-nx/build-automation] Modern build tools, such as Make, Gradle and Bazel, often incorporate incremental build capabilities to streamline development workflows.
[src:monorepo-nx/build-automation] While incremental builds offer significant performance advantages, they also introduce challenges, such as ensuring the accuracy of dependency tracking and avoiding stale or inconsistent build artifacts.
[src:monorepo-nx/build-automation] To address these issues, some build systems provide mechanisms for "clean builds," which rebuild the entire project from scratch to guarantee correctness when necessary.
[src:monorepo-nx/build-automation] Because of this issue, incremental builds are rarely used in continuous integration systems, where correctness is preferred to compilation speed.
[src:monorepo-nx/build-automation] Tools such as Make can be used via custom configuration file or using the command-line.
[src:monorepo-nx/build-automation] Custom tools such as shell scripts can also be used, although they become increasingly cumbersome as the codebase grows more complex.
[src:monorepo-nx/build-automation] Some tools, such as shell scripts, are task-oriented declarative programming.
[src:monorepo-nx/build-automation] They encode sequences of commands to perform with usually minimal conditional logic.
[src:monorepo-nx/build-automation] Some tools, such as Make are product-oriented.
[src:monorepo-nx/build-automation] They build a product, a.k.a. target, based on configured dependencies.
[src:monorepo-nx/build-automation] A build server is a server setup to run builds.
[src:monorepo-nx/build-automation] In contrast to a personal computer, a server allows for a more consistent and available build environment.
[src:monorepo-nx/build-automation] Traditionally, a build server was a local computer dedicated as a shared resource instead of used as a personal computer.
[src:monorepo-nx/build-automation] Today, there are many cloud computing, software as a service (SaaS) websites for building.
[src:monorepo-nx/build-automation] A continuous integration server is a build server that is setup to build in a relatively frequent way, often on each code commit.
[src:monorepo-nx/build-automation] A build server may also be incorporated into a tool for application release automation (ARA) or application lifecycle management (ALM).
[src:monorepo-nx/build-automation] Automating the build process is a required step for implementing continuous integration and continuous delivery (CI/CD), all of which are considered best practices for software development.
[src:monorepo-nx/continuous-integration] The earliest known work (1989) on continuous integration was the Infuse environment developed by G.
[src:monorepo-nx/continuous-integration] In 1997, Kent Beck and Ron Jeffries invented extreme programming (XP) while on the Chrysler Comprehensive Compensation System project, including continuous integration.
[src:monorepo-nx/continuous-integration] Beck published about continuous integration in 1998, emphasising the importance of face-to-face communication over technological support.
[src:monorepo-nx/continuous-integration] In 1999, Beck elaborated more in his first full book on Extreme Programming.
[src:monorepo-nx/continuous-integration] CruiseControl, one of the first open-source CI tools, was released in 2001.
[src:monorepo-nx/continuous-integration] In 2010, Timothy Fitz published an article detailing how IMVU's engineering team had built and been using the first practical CD system.
[src:monorepo-nx/continuous-integration] While his post was originally met with skepticism, it quickly caught on and found widespread adoption as part of the lean software development methodology, also based on IMVU.
[src:monorepo-nx/continuous-integration] The core activities of CI are that developers co-locate code changes in a shared, integration area frequently and that the resulting integrated codebase is verified for correctness.
[src:monorepo-nx/continuous-integration] The first part generally involves merging changes to a common version control branch.
[src:monorepo-nx/continuous-integration] The second part generally involves automated processes including: building, testing and many other processes.
[src:monorepo-nx/continuous-integration] Typically, a server builds from the integration area frequently, i.e. after each commit or periodically, like once a day.
[src:monorepo-nx/continuous-integration] The server may perform quality control checks such as running unit tests and collect software quality metrics via processes such as static analysis and performance testing.
[src:monorepo-nx/continuous-integration] Build automation tools automate building.
[src:monorepo-nx/continuous-integration] Proponents of CI recommend that a single command should have the capability of building the system.
[src:monorepo-nx/continuous-integration] Automation often includes automating the integration, which often includes deployment into a production-like environment.
[src:monorepo-nx/continuous-integration] In many cases, the build script not only compiles binaries but also generates documentation, website pages, statistics and distribution media (such as Debian DEB, Red Hat RPM or Windows MSI files).
[src:monorepo-nx/continuous-integration] CI requires the version control system to support atomic commits; in other words, all of a developer's changes are handled as a single commit.
[src:monorepo-nx/continuous-integration] When making a code change, a developer creates a branch that is a copy of the current codebase.
[src:monorepo-nx/continuous-integration] As other changes are committed to the repository, this copy diverges from the latest version.
[src:monorepo-nx/continuous-integration] The longer development continues on a branch without merging to the integration branch, the greater the risk of multiple integration conflicts and failures when the developer branch is eventually merged back.
[src:monorepo-nx/continuous-integration] When developers submit code to the repository they must first update their code to reflect the changes in the repository since they took their copy.
[src:monorepo-nx/continuous-integration] The more changes the repository contains, the more work developers must do before submitting their own changes.
[src:monorepo-nx/continuous-integration] Eventually, the repository may become so different from the developers' baselines that they enter what is sometimes referred to as "merge hell", or "integration hell", where the time it takes to integrate exceeds the time it took to make their original changes.
[src:monorepo-nx/continuous-integration] Proponents of CI suggest that developers should use test-driven development and to ensure that all unit tests pass locally before committing to the integration branch so that one developer's work does not break another developer's copy.
[src:monorepo-nx/continuous-integration] Incomplete features can be disabled before committing, using feature toggles.
[src:monorepo-nx/continuous-integration] Continuous delivery ensures the software checked in on an integration branch is always in a state that can be deployed to users, and continuous deployment automates the deployment process.
[src:monorepo-nx/continuous-integration] Proponents of CI recommend storing all files and information needed for building in version control (for git a *repository*), and that the system should be buildable from a fresh checkout and not require additional dependencies.
[src:monorepo-nx/continuous-integration] Martin Fowler recommends that all developers commit to the same integration branch.
[src:monorepo-nx/continuous-integration] Developers can reduce the effort of resolving conflicting changes by synchronizing changes with each other frequently, at least daily.
[src:monorepo-nx/continuous-integration] Checking in a week's worth of work risks conflict both in likelihood of occurrence and complexity to resolve.
[src:monorepo-nx/continuous-integration] Relatively small conflicts are significantly easier to resolve than larger ones.
[src:monorepo-nx/continuous-integration] Integrating (committing) changes at least once a day is considered good practice, and more often better.
[src:monorepo-nx/continuous-integration] Building daily, if not more often, is generally recommended.
[src:monorepo-nx/continuous-integration] The system should build commits to the current working version to verify that they integrate correctly.
[src:monorepo-nx/continuous-integration] A common practice is to use Automated Continuous Integration, although this may be done manually.
[src:monorepo-nx/continuous-integration] Automated continuous integration employs a continuous integration server or daemon to monitor the revision control system for changes, then automatically run the build process.
[src:monorepo-nx/continuous-integration] When fixing a bug, it is a good practice to push a test case that reproduces the bug.
[src:monorepo-nx/continuous-integration] This prevents the fix from being reverted and the bug from reappearing, which is known as a regression.
[src:monorepo-nx/continuous-integration] The build needs to complete rapidly so that if there is a problem with integration, it is quickly identified.
[src:monorepo-nx/continuous-integration] Having a test environment can lead to failures in tested systems when they deploy in the production environment because the production environment may differ from the test environment in a significant way.
[src:monorepo-nx/continuous-integration] However, building a replica of a production environment is cost-prohibitive.
[src:monorepo-nx/continuous-integration] Instead, the test environment or a separate pre-production environment ("staging") should be built to be a scalable version of the production environment to alleviate costs while maintaining technology stack composition and nuances.
[src:monorepo-nx/continuous-integration] Within these test environments, service virtualisation is commonly used to obtain on-demand access to dependencies (e.g., APIs, third-party applications, services, mainframes, etc.) that are beyond the team's control, still evolving, or too complex to configure in a virtual test lab.
[src:monorepo-nx/continuous-integration] Making builds readily available to stakeholders and testers can reduce the amount of rework necessary when rebuilding a feature that doesn't meet requirements.
[src:monorepo-nx/continuous-integration] Additionally, early testing reduces the chances that defects survive until deployment.
[src:monorepo-nx/continuous-integration] Finding errors earlier can reduce the amount of work necessary to resolve them.
[src:monorepo-nx/continuous-integration] All programmers should start the day by updating the project from the repository.
[src:monorepo-nx/continuous-integration] That way, they will all stay up to date.
[src:monorepo-nx/continuous-integration] It should be easy to find out whether the build breaks and, if so, who made the relevant change and what that change was.
[src:monorepo-nx/continuous-integration] Most CI systems allow the running of scripts after a build finishes.
[src:monorepo-nx/continuous-integration] In most situations, it is possible to write a script to deploy the application to a live test server that everyone can look at.
[src:monorepo-nx/continuous-integration] A further advance in this way of thinking is continuous deployment, which calls for the software to be deployed directly into production, often with additional automation to prevent defects or regressions.
[src:monorepo-nx/getting-started-intro] It helps you **develop faster** and **keep CI fast** as your codebase scales.
[src:monorepo-nx/getting-started-intro] Monorepos have many advantages and are especially powerful for AI-assisted development.
[src:monorepo-nx/getting-started-intro] **Understands your codebase** - Builds project and task graphs showing how everything connects.
[src:monorepo-nx/getting-started-intro] **Orchestrates intelligently** - Runs tasks in the right order, parallelizing when possible.
[src:monorepo-nx/getting-started-intro] **Enforces boundaries** - Module boundary rules prevent unwanted dependencies between projects.
[src:monorepo-nx/getting-started-intro] **Handles flakiness** - Automatically re-runs flaky tasks and self-heals CI failures.
[src:monorepo-nx/getting-started-intro] Start with the CLI and add capabilities as your needs grow.
[src:monorepo-nx/monorepo] In version-control systems, a **monorepo** or **monorepository** ("mono" meaning 'single' and "repo" being short for 'repository') is a software-development strategy in which the code for a number of projects is stored in the same repository.
[src:monorepo-nx/monorepo] This practice dates back to at least the early 2000s, when it was commonly called a shared codebase.
[src:monorepo-nx/monorepo] Google, Meta, Microsoft, Uber, Airbnb, and Twitter all employ very large monorepos with varying strategies to scale build systems and version control software with a large volume of code and daily changes.
[src:monorepo-nx/monorepo] A related concept is a monolithic application, but whereas a monolith combines its sub-projects into one large project, a monorepo may contain multiple independent projects.
[src:monorepo-nx/monorepo] In a multiple repository environment where multiple projects depend on a third-party dependency, that dependency might be downloaded or built multiple times.
[src:monorepo-nx/monorepo] In a monorepo the build can be easily optimized, as referenced dependencies all exist in the same codebase.
[src:monorepo-nx/monorepo] When projects that work together are contained in separate repositories, releases need to sync which versions of one project work with the other.
[src:monorepo-nx/monorepo] In a monorepo this problem can be negated, since developers may change multiple projects atomically.
[src:monorepo-nx/monorepo] Since developers have access to the entire project, refactors can ensure that every piece of the project continues to function after a refactor.
[src:monorepo-nx/monorepo] teams can improve projects being worked on by other teams.
[src:monorepo-nx/monorepo] Although not required, some monorepo builds use one version number across all projects in the repository.
[src:monorepo-nx/monorepo] With split repositories, access to a repository can be granted based upon need.
[src:monorepo-nx/monorepo] A monorepo allows read access to all software in the project, possibly presenting new security issues.
[src:monorepo-nx/monorepo] Note that there are versioning systems in which this limitation is not an issue.
[src:monorepo-nx/monorepo] is used, it's possible to download any part of the repo (even a single directory), and path-based authorization can be used to restrict access to certain parts of a repository.
[src:monorepo-nx/monorepo] With split repositories, you fetch only the project you are interested in by default.
[src:monorepo-nx/monorepo] This can take up a significant amount of storage space.
[src:monorepo-nx/monorepo] doing so defeats some of the advantages of a monorepo.
[src:monorepo-nx/monorepo] Companies with large projects have come across hurdles with monorepos, specifically concerning build tools and version control systems.
[src:monorepo-nx/monorepo] Google's monorepo, speculated to be the largest in the world, meets the classification of an ultra-large-scale system and must handle tens of thousands of contributions every day in a repository over 80 terabytes in size.
[src:monorepo-nx/monorepo] Companies using or switching to existing version control software found that software could not efficiently handle the amount of data required for a large monorepo.
[src:monorepo-nx/monorepo] Facebook and Microsoft chose to contribute to or fork existing version control software Mercurial and Git respectively, while Google eventually created their own version control system.
[src:monorepo-nx/monorepo] For more than ten years, Google had relied on Perforce hosted on a single machine.
[src:monorepo-nx/monorepo] In 2005 Google's build servers could get locked up to 10 minutes at a time.
[src:monorepo-nx/monorepo] Google improved this to 30 seconds–1 minute in 2010.
[src:monorepo-nx/monorepo] Due to scaling issues, Google eventually developed its own in-house distributed version control system dubbed Piper.
[src:monorepo-nx/monorepo] Facebook ran into performance issues with the version control system Mercurial and made upstream contributions to the client, and in January 2014 made it faster than a competing solution in Git.
[src:monorepo-nx/monorepo] In May 2017 Microsoft announced that virtually all of its Windows engineers use a Git monorepo.
[src:monorepo-nx/monorepo] In the transition, Microsoft made substantial upstream contributions to the Git client to remove unnecessary file access and improve handling of large files with Virtual File System for Git.
[src:monorepo-nx/monorepo] Few build tools work well in a monorepo, and flows where builds and continuous integration testing of the entire repository are performed upon check-in will cause performance problems.
[src:monorepo-nx/monorepo] A build system that processes dependencies as a directed graph (such as Buck, Bazel, Please, or Pants) solves this by compartmentalizing each build or test to the active area of development.
[src:monorepo-nx/monorepo] Twitter began development of Pants in 2011, as both Facebook's Buck and Google's Bazel were closed-source at the time.
[src:monorepo-nx/monorepo] Twitter open-sourced Pants in 2012 under the Apache 2.0 License.
[src:monorepo-nx/monorepo] Please is a Go-based build system; it was developed in 2016 by Thought Machine, whose developers were both inspired by Google's Bazel and dissatisfied with Facebook's Buck.
[src:monorepo-nx/software-repository] A **software repository**, or **repo** for short, is a storage location for software packages.
[src:monorepo-nx/software-repository] Often a table of contents is also stored, along with metadata.
[src:monorepo-nx/software-repository] A software repository is typically managed by source or version control, or repository managers.
[src:monorepo-nx/software-repository] Package managers allow automatically installing and updating repositories, sometimes called "packages".
[src:monorepo-nx/software-repository] Many software publishers and other organizations maintain servers on the Internet for this purpose, either free of charge or for a subscription fee.
[src:monorepo-nx/software-repository] Repositories may be solely for particular programs, such as CPAN for the Perl programming language, or for an entire operating system.
[src:monorepo-nx/software-repository] Operators of such repositories typically provide a package management system, tools intended to search for, install and otherwise manipulate software packages from the repositories.
[src:monorepo-nx/software-repository] For example, many Linux distributions use Advanced Packaging Tool (APT), commonly found in Debian based distributions, or Yellowdog Updater, Modified (yum) found in Red Hat based distributions.
[src:monorepo-nx/software-repository] There are also multiple independent package management systems, such as pacman, used in Arch Linux and equo, found in Sabayon Linux.
[src:monorepo-nx/software-repository] As software repositories are designed to include useful packages, major repositories are designed to be malware free.
[src:monorepo-nx/software-repository] If a computer is configured to use a digitally signed repository from a reputable vendor, and is coupled with an appropriate permissions system, this significantly reduces the threat of malware to these systems.
[src:monorepo-nx/software-repository] As a side effect, many systems that have these abilities do not need anti-malware software such as antivirus software.
[src:monorepo-nx/software-repository] Most major Linux distributions have many repositories around the world that mirror the main repository.
[src:monorepo-nx/software-repository] At client side, a package manager helps installing from and updating the repositories.
[src:monorepo-nx/software-repository] A package management system is different from a package development process.
[src:monorepo-nx/software-repository] A typical use of a package management system is to facilitate the integration of code from possibly different sources into a coherent stand-alone operating unit.
[src:monorepo-nx/software-repository] Thus, a package management system might be used to produce a distribution of Linux, possibly a distribution tailored to a specific restricted application.
[src:monorepo-nx/software-repository] A package development process, by contrast, is used to manage the co-development of code and documentation of a collection of functions or routines with a common theme, producing thereby a package of software functions that typically will not be complete and usable by themselves.
[src:monorepo-nx/software-repository] A good package development process will help users conform to good documentation and coding practices, integrating some level of unit testing.
[src:monorepo-nx/software-repository] The following table lists a few languages with repositories for contributed software.
[src:monorepo-nx/software-repository] The "Autochecks" column describes the routine checks done.
[src:monorepo-nx/software-repository] Very few people have the ability to test their software under multiple operating systems with different versions of the core code and with other contributed packages they may use.
[src:monorepo-nx/software-repository] For the R programming language, the Comprehensive R Archive Network (CRAN) runs tests routinely.
[src:monorepo-nx/software-repository] To understand how this is valuable, imagine a situation with two developers, Sally and John.
[src:monorepo-nx/software-repository] Sally only runs the current version of the software under one version of Microsoft Windows, and has only tested it in that environment.
[src:monorepo-nx/software-repository] At more or less regular intervals, CRAN tests Sally's contribution under a dozen combinations of operating systems and versions of the core R language software.
[src:monorepo-nx/software-repository] If one of them generates an error, she gets that error message.
[src:monorepo-nx/software-repository] With luck, that error message details may provide enough input to allow enable a fix for the error, even if she cannot replicate it with her current hardware and software.
[src:monorepo-nx/software-repository] Next, suppose John contributes to the repository a package B that uses a package A.
[src:monorepo-nx/software-repository] Package B passes all the tests and is made available to users.
[src:monorepo-nx/software-repository] Later, Sally submits an improved version of A, which breaks B.
[src:monorepo-nx/software-repository] The autochecks make it possible to provide information to John so he can fix the problem.
[src:monorepo-nx/software-repository] This example exposes both a strength and a weakness in the R contributed-package system: CRAN supports this kind of automated testing of contributed packages, but packages contributed to CRAN need not specify the versions of other contributed packages that they use.
[src:monorepo-nx/software-repository] Procedures for requesting specific versions of packages exist, but contributors might not use those procedures.
[src:monorepo-nx/software-repository] Beyond this, a repository such as CRAN running regular checks of contributed packages actually provides an extensive if *ad hoc* test suite for development versions of the core language.
[src:monorepo-nx/software-repository] If Sally (in the example above) gets an error message she does not understand or thinks is inappropriate, especially from a development version of the language, she can (and often does with R) ask the core development-team for the language for help.
[src:monorepo-nx/software-repository] In this way, the repository can contribute to improving the quality of the core language software.
[src:monorepo-nx/software-repository] Package managers help manage repositories and the distribution of them.
[src:monorepo-nx/software-repository] If a repository is updated, a package manager will usually allow a user to update that repository through the manager.
[src:monorepo-nx/software-repository] It also helps to manage things such as dependencies between other repositories.
[src:monorepo-nx/software-repository] In an enterprise environment, a software repository is usually used to store artifacts, or to mirror external repositories which may be inaccessible due to security restrictions.
[src:monorepo-nx/software-repository] One example is Sonatype Nexus Repository.
[src:monorepo-nx/software-repository] At server side, a software repository is typically managed by source control or repository managers.
[src:monorepo-nx/software-repository] Some of the repository managers allow to aggregate other repository location into one URL and provide a caching proxy.
[src:monorepo-nx/software-repository] When doing continuous builds many artifacts are produced and often centrally stored, so automatically deleting the ones which are not released is important.
[src:monorepo-nx/software-repository] As part of the development lifecycle, source code is continuously being built into binary artifacts using continuous integration.
[src:monorepo-nx/software-repository] This may interact with a binary repository manager much like a developer would by getting artifacts from the repositories and pushing builds there.
[src:monorepo-nx/software-repository] Artifacts and packages inherently mean different things.
[src:monorepo-nx/software-repository] Artifacts are simply an output or collection of files (ex.
[src:monorepo-nx/software-repository] JAR, WAR, DLLS, RPM etc.) and one of those files may contain metadata (e.g.
[src:monorepo-nx/software-repository] Whereas packages are a single archive file in a well-defined format (ex.
[src:monorepo-nx/software-repository] NuGet) that contain files appropriate for the package type (ex.
[src:monorepo-nx/software-repository] Many artifacts result from builds but other types are crucial as well.
[src:monorepo-nx/software-repository] Packages are essentially one of two things: a library or an application.
[src:monorepo-nx/software-repository] Compared to source files, binary artifacts are often larger by orders of magnitude, they are rarely deleted or overwritten (except for rare cases such as snapshots or nightly builds), and they are usually accompanied by much metadata such as id, package name, version, license and more.
[src:monorepo-nx/software-repository] Metadata describes a binary artifact, is stored and specified separately from the artifact itself, and can have several additional uses.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] Version control is a component of software configuration management.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] A **version control system** is a software tool that automates version control.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] Alternatively, version control is embedded as a feature of some systems such as word processors, spreadsheets, collaborative web docs, and content management systems, such as Wikipedia's page history.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] Version control includes options to view old versions and to revert a file to a previous version.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] As teams develop software, it is common to deploy multiple versions of the same software, and for different developers to work on one or more different versions simultaneously.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] Bugs or features of the software are often only present in certain versions (because of the fixing of some problems and the introduction of others as the program develops).
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] Therefore, for the purposes of locating and fixing bugs, it is vitally important to be able to retrieve and run different versions of the software to determine in which version(s) the problem occurs.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] It may also be necessary to develop two versions of the software concurrently: for instance, where one version has bugs fixed, but no new features (branch), while the other version is where new features are worked on (trunk).
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] At the simplest level, developers could simply retain multiple copies of the different versions of the program, and label them appropriately.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] This simple approach has been used in many large software projects.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] While this method can work, it is inefficient as many near-identical copies of the program have to be maintained.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] This requires a lot of self-discipline on the part of developers and often leads to mistakes.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] Since the code base is the same, it also requires granting read-write-execute permission to a set of developers, and this adds the pressure of someone managing permissions so that the code base is not compromised, which adds more complexity.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] Consequently, systems to automate some or all of the revision control process have been developed.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] This abstracts most operational steps (hides them from ordinary users).
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] Moreover, in software development, legal and business practice, and other environments, it has become increasingly common for a single document or snippet of code to be edited by a team, the members of which may be geographically dispersed and may pursue different and even contrary interests.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] Sophisticated revision control that tracks and accounts for ownership of changes to documents and code may be extremely helpful or even indispensable in such situations.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] Revision control may also track changes to configuration files, such as those typically stored in `/etc` or `/usr/local/etc` on Unix systems.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] This gives system administrators another way to easily track changes made and a way to roll back to earlier versions should the need arise.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] Many version control systems identify the version of a file as a number or letter, called the *version number*, *version*, *revision number*, *revision*, or *revision level*.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] For example, the first version of a file might be version *1*.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] When the file is changed the next version is *2*.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] Each version is associated with a timestamp and the person making the change.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] Revisions can be compared, restored, and, with some types of files, merged.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] IBM's OS/360 IEBUPDTE software update tool dates back to 1962, arguably a precursor to version control system tools.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] Two source management and version control packages that were heavily used by IBM 360/370 installations were The Librarian and Panvalet.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] A full system designed for source code control was started in 1972: the Source Code Control System (SCCS), again for the OS/360.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] SCCS's user manual, especially the introduction, which was published on December 4, 1975, implied that it was the first deliberate revision control system.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] The Revision Control System (RCS) followed in 1982 and, later, Concurrent Versions System (CVS) added network and concurrent development features to RCS.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] After CVS, a dominant successor was Subversion, followed by the rise of distributed version control tools such as Git.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] Revision control manages changes to a set of data over time.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] These changes can be structured in various ways.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] Often the data is thought of as a collection of many individual items, such as files or documents, and changes to individual files are tracked.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] This is in line with the notion of keeping files separate but causes problems when identity changes, which happens when files are renamed, split or merged.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] Accordingly, some systems such as Git, consider changes to the data as a whole instead, which is less intuitive for simple changes but simplifies more complex changes.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] As a simple example, when editing a computer file, the data stored in memory by the editing program is the working copy, which is committed by saving the file.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] Concretely, one may print out a document, edit it by hand, and only later manually input the changes into a computer and save it.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] For source code control, the working copy is instead a copy of all files in a particular revision, generally stored locally on the developer's computer; in this case saving the file only changes the working copy, and checking into the repository is a separate step.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] If multiple people are working on a single data set or document, they are implicitly creating branches of the data (in their working copies), and thus issues of merging arise, as discussed below.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] For simple collaborative document editing, this can be prevented by using file locking or simply avoiding working on the same document that someone else is working on.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] Revision control systems are often centralized, with a single authoritative data store, the *repository,* and check-outs and check-ins done with reference to this central repository.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] Alternatively, in distributed revision control, no single repository is authoritative, and data can be checked out and checked into any repository.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] When checking into a different repository, this is interpreted as a merge or patch.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] In terms of graph theory, revisions are generally thought of as a line of development (the *trunk*) with branches off of this, forming a directed tree, visualized as one or more parallel lines of development (the "mainlines" of the branches) branching off a trunk.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] In reality the structure is more complicated, forming a directed acyclic graph, but for many purposes "tree with merges" is an adequate approximation.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] Revisions occur in sequence over time, and thus can be arranged in order, either by revision number or timestamp.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] Revisions are based on past revisions, though it is possible to largely or completely replace an earlier revision, such as "delete all existing text, insert new text".
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] In the simplest case, with no branching or undoing, each revision is based on its immediate predecessor alone, and they form a simple line, with a single latest version, the "HEAD" revision or *tip*.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] In graph theory terms, drawing each revision as a point and each "derived revision" relationship as an arrow (conventionally pointing from older to newer, in the same direction as time), this is a linear graph.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] In principle the resulting tree need not have a preferred tip ("main" latest revision) – just various different revisions – but in practice one tip is generally identified as HEAD.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] When a new revision is based on HEAD, it is either identified as the new HEAD, or considered a new branch.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] This most often occurs when changes occur in multiple branches (most often two, but more are possible), which are then merged into a single branch incorporating both changes.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] If these changes overlap, it may be difficult or impossible to merge, and require manual intervention or rewriting.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] In the presence of merges, the resulting graph is no longer a tree, as nodes can have multiple parents, but is instead a rooted directed acyclic graph (DAG).
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] The graph is acyclic since parents are always backwards in time, and rooted because there is an oldest version.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] Assuming there is a trunk, merges from branches can be considered as "external" to the tree – the changes in the branch are packaged up as a *patch,* which is applied to HEAD (of the trunk), creating a new revision without any explicit reference to the branch, and preserving the tree structure.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] Thus, while the actual relations between versions form a DAG, this can be considered a tree plus merges, and the trunk itself is a line.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] In distributed revision control, in the presence of multiple repositories these may be based on a single original version (a root of the tree), but there need not be an original root - instead there can be a separate root (oldest revision) for each repository.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] This can happen, for example, if two people start working on a project separately.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] Similarly, in the presence of multiple data sets (multiple projects) that exchange data or merge, there is no single root, though for simplicity one may think of one project as primary and the other as secondary, merged into the first with or without its own revision history.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] Engineering revision control developed from formalized processes based on tracking revisions of early blueprints or bluelines*"MIL-STD-100G: Department of Defense Standard Practice for Engineering Drawings" (PDF).
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] This system of control implicitly allowed returning to an earlier state of the design, for cases in which an engineering dead-end was reached in the development of the design.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] A revision table was used to keep track of the changes made.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] Additionally, the modified areas of the drawing were highlighted using revision clouds.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] Version control is widespread in business and law.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] Indeed, "contract redline" and "legal blackline" are some of the earliest forms of revision control, and are still employed in business and law with varying degrees of sophistication.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] The most sophisticated techniques are beginning to be used for the electronic tracking of changes to CAD files (see product data management), supplanting the "manual" electronic implementation of traditional revision control.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] Game development often involves large binary files and teams working together across different disciplines.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] As a result, game studios use version control systems with good support for large binary files, file locking, and fast synchronization.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] Common tools include Perforce and several newer cloud-based systems.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] Traditional revision control systems use a centralized model where all the revision control functions take place on a shared server.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] If two developers try to change the same file at the same time, without some method of managing access the developers may end up overwriting each other's work.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] Centralized revision control systems solve this problem in one of two different "source management models": file locking and version merging.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] An operation is *atomic* if the system is left in a consistent state even if the operation is interrupted.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] The *commit* operation is usually the most critical in this sense.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] Commits tell the revision control system to make a group of changes final, and available to all users.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] Not all revision control systems have atomic commits; Concurrent Versions System lacks this feature.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] The simplest method of preventing "concurrent access" problems involves locking files so that only one developer at a time has write access to the central "repository" copies of those files.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] Once one developer "checks out" a file, others can read that file, but no one else may change that file until that developer "checks in" the updated version (or cancels the checkout).
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] File locking has both merits and drawbacks.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] It can provide some protection against difficult merge conflicts when a user is making radical changes to many sections of a large file (or group of files).
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] If the files are left exclusively locked for too long, other developers may be tempted to bypass the revision control software and change the files locally, forcing a difficult manual merge when the other changes are finally checked in.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] In a large organization, files can be left "checked out" and locked and forgotten about as developers move between projects - these tools may or may not make it easy to see who has a file checked out.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] Most version control systems allow multiple developers to edit the same file at the same time.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] The first developer to "check in" changes to the central repository always succeeds.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] The system may provide facilities to merge further changes into the central repository, and preserve the changes from the first developer when other developers check in.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] Merging two files can be a very delicate operation, and usually possible only if the data structure is simple, as in text files.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] The result of a merge of two image files might not result in an image file at all.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] The second developer checking in files will need to take care with the merge, to make sure that the changes are compatible and that the merge operation does not introduce its own logic errors within the files.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] These problems limit the availability of automatic or semi-automatic merge operations mainly to simple text-based documents, unless a specific merge plugin is available for the file types.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] The concept of a *reserved edit* can provide an optional means to explicitly lock a file for exclusive write access, even when a merging capability exists.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] Most revision control tools will use only one of these similar terms (baseline, label, tag) to refer to the action of identifying a snapshot ("label the project") or the record of the snapshot ("try it with baseline *X*").
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] Typically only one of the terms *baseline*, *label*, or *tag* is used in documentation or discussion ; they can be considered synonyms.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] In most projects, some snapshots are more significant than others, such as those used to indicate published releases, branches, or milestones.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] When both the term *baseline* and either of *label* or *tag* are used together in the same context, *label* and *tag* usually refer to the mechanism within the tool of identifying or making the record of the snapshot, and *baseline* indicates the increased significance of any given label or tag.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] Most formal discussion of configuration management uses the term *baseline*.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] Distributed revision control systems (DRCS) take a peer-to-peer approach, as opposed to the client–server approach of centralized systems.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] Rather than a single, central repository on which clients synchronize, each peer's working copy of the codebase is a bona-fide repository.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] Distributed revision control conducts synchronization by exchanging patches (change-sets) from peer to peer.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] Rather, communication is only necessary when pushing or pulling changes to or from other peers.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] Following best practices is necessary to obtain the full benefits of version control.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] Best practice may vary by version control tool and the field to which version control is applied.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] Other software development best practices such as code review and automated regression testing may assist in the following of version control best practices.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] Costs and benefits will vary dependent upon the version control tool chosen and the field in which it is applied.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] This section speaks to the field of software development, where version control is widely applied.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] In addition to the costs of licensing the version control software, using version control requires time and effort.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] The concepts underlying version control must be understood and the technical particulars required to operate the version control software chosen must be learned.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] Version control best practices must be learned and integrated into the organization's existing software development practices.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] Management effort may be required to maintain the discipline needed to follow best practices in order to obtain useful benefit.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] A core benefit is the ability to keep history and revert changes, allowing the developer to easily undo changes.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] This gives the developer more opportunity to experiment, eliminating the fear of breaking existing code.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] Branching assists with deployment and release management.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] There can be damage mitigation, accountability, process and design improvement, and other benefits associated with the record keeping provided by version control, the tracking of who did what, when, why, and how.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] When bugs arise, knowing what was done when helps with damage mitigation and recovery by assisting in the identification of what problems exist, how long they have existed, and determining problem scope and solutions.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] Previous versions can be installed and tested to verify conclusions reached by examination of code and commit messages.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] Version control can greatly simplify debugging.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] The application of a test case to multiple versions can quickly identify the change which introduced a bug.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] The developer need not be familiar with the entire code base and can focus instead on the code that introduced the problem.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] Version control enhances collaboration in multiple ways.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] Since version control can identify conflicting changes, i.e. incompatible changes made to the same lines of code, there is less need for coordination among developers.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] The packaging of commits, branches, and all the associated commit messages and version labels, improves communication between developers, both in the moment and over time.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] Better communication, whether instant or deferred, can improve the code review process, the testing process, and other critical aspects of the software development process.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] Some of the more advanced revision-control tools offer many other facilities, allowing deeper integration with other tools and software-engineering processes.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] Plugins are often available for IDEs such as Oracle JDeveloper, IntelliJ IDEA, Eclipse, Visual Studio, Delphi, NetBeans IDE, Xcode, and GNU Emacs (via vc.el).
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] Advanced research prototypes generate appropriate commit messages.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] An approved revision of a document or source file to which subsequent changes can be made.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] A search for the author and revision that last modified a particular line.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] A set of files under version control may be *branched* or *forked* at a point in time so that, from that time forward, two copies of those files may develop at different speeds or in different ways independently of each other.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] A *change* (or *diff*, or *delta*) represents a specific modification to a document under version control.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] The granularity of the modification considered a change varies between version control systems.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] On many version control systems with atomic multi-change commits, a *change list* (or *CL*), *change set*, *update*, or *patch* identifies the set of *changes* made in a single commit.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] This can also represent a sequential view of the source code, allowing the examination of source as of any particular changelist ID.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] To *check out* (or *co*) is to create a local working copy from the repository.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] A user may specify a specific revision or obtain the latest.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] The term 'checkout' can also be used as a noun to describe the working copy.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] When a file has been checked out from a shared file server, it cannot be edited by other users.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] Think of it like a hotel, when you check out, you no longer have access to its amenities.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] In version control software, a changeset (also known as commit and revision) is a set of alterations packaged together, along with meta-information about the alterations.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] A changeset describes the exact differences between two successive versions in the version control system's repository of changes.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] Changesets are typically treated as an atomic unit, an indivisible set, by version control systems.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] To *commit* (*check in*, *ci* or, more rarely, *install*, *submit* or *record*) is to write or merge the changes made in the working copy back to the repository.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] A commit contains metadata, typically the author information and a commit message that describes the change.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] A short note, written by the developer, stored with the commit, which describes the commit.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] Ideally, it records why the modification was made, a description of the modification's effect or purpose, and non-obvious aspects of how the change works.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] A conflict occurs when different parties make changes to the same document, and the system is unable to reconcile the changes.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] A user must *resolve* the conflict by combining the changes, or by selecting one change in favour of the other.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] Most revision control software uses delta compression, which retains only the differences between successive versions of files.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] This allows for more efficient storage of many different versions of files.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] A stream in which some or all file versions are mirrors of the parent stream's versions.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] The process of merging changes made in the main *trunk* into a development (feature or team) branch.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] Also sometimes called *tip*, this refers to the most recent commit, either to the trunk or to a branch.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] The trunk and each branch have their own head, though HEAD is sometimes loosely used to refer to the trunk.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] Some revision control software uses Interleaved deltas, a method that allows storing the history of text based files in a more efficient way than by using Delta compression.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] When a developer *locks* a file, no one else can update that file until it is unlocked.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] Locking can be supported by the version control system, or via informal communications between developers (aka *social locking*).
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] Similar to *trunk*, but there can be a mainline for each branch.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] A *merge* or *integration* is an operation in which two sets of changes are applied to a file or set of files.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] The act of copying file content from a less controlled location into a more controlled location.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] For example, from a user's workspace into a repository, or from a stream to its parent.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] Copy revisions from one repository into another.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] *Pull* is initiated by the receiving repository, while *push* is initiated by the source.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] *Fetch* is sometimes used as a synonym for *pull*, or to mean a *pull* followed by an *update*.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] Contributions to a source code repository that uses a distributed version control system are commonly made by means of a pull request, also known as a merge request.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] The contributor requests that the project maintainer *pull* the source code change, hence the name "pull request".
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] The maintainer has to *merge* the pull request if the contribution should become part of the source base.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] The developer creates a pull request to notify maintainers of a new change; a comment thread is associated with each pull request.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] This allows for focused discussion of code changes.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] Submitted pull requests are visible to anyone with repository access.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] A pull request can be accepted or rejected by maintainers.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] Once the pull request is reviewed and approved, it is merged into the repository.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] Depending on the established workflow, the code may need to be tested before being included into official release.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] Therefore, some projects contain a special branch for merging untested pull requests.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] Other projects run an automated test suite on every pull request, using a continuous integration tool, and the reviewer checks that any new code has appropriate test coverage.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] In version control systems, a repository is a data structure that stores metadata for a set of files or directory structure.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] Depending on whether the version control system in use is distributed, like Git or Mercurial, or centralized, like Subversion, CVS, or Perforce, the whole set of information in the repository may be duplicated on every user's system or may be maintained on a single server.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] Some of the metadata that a repository contains includes, among other things, a historical record of changes in the repository, a set of commit objects, and a set of references to commit objects, called *heads*.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] The act of user intervention to address a conflict between different changes to the same document.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] The process of merging different team branches into the main trunk of the versioning system.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] In SVK, a Revision is the state at a point in time of the entire tree in the repository.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] The act of making one file or folder available in multiple branches at the same time.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] When a shared file is changed in one branch, it is changed in other branches.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] A container for branched files that has a known relationship to other such containers.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] Streams form a hierarchy; each stream can inherit various properties (like versions, namespace, workflow rules, subscribers, etc.) from its parent stream.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] A *tag* or *label* refers to an important snapshot in time, consistent across many files.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] These files at that point may all be tagged with a user-friendly, meaningful name or revision number.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] An *update* (or *sync*, but *sync* can also mean a combined *push* and *pull*) merges changes made in the repository (by other people, for example) into the local *working copy*.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] *Update* is also the term used by some CM tools (CM+, PLS, SMS) for the change package concept (see *changelist*).
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] The *working copy* is the local copy of files from a repository, at a specific time or revision.
[src:monorepo-nx/version-control] All work done to the files in a repository is initially done on a working copy, hence the name.
